<!--article-->
<worksheet margin="1in" bottom="1.25cm">
    <title>Math 483 Homework 2</title>

            
	<objectives>
		<ul>
			<li>
				<p>
					Review some convergence of series of functions (pointwise and uniform).
				</p>
			</li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Prove a test for uniform and absolute convergence of series.
                </p>
            </li>
	  	</ul>
    </objectives>
<page>

<exercise><title>Two Convergence Facts for Series</title>
<introduction>
    <p>
        In order to work with series of functions, we need to be able to work with series of numbers.
    </p>
</introduction>
<task>
    <statement>
        <p>
            Let <m>\{a_k\}_{k=0}^{\infty}</m> be a sequence of real numbers. Define what it means for the series
            <md>
                \sum_{k=0}^{\infty} a_k
            </md>
            to converge.
        </p>
    </statement>
</task>
<task>
    <statement>
        <p>
            Prove the Comparison Test: If <m>\{a_k\}_{k=0}^{\infty}</m> and <m>\{b_k\}_{k=0}^{\infty}</m> are sequences with <m>0\leq a_k \leq b_k</m> and <m>\sum_\limits{k=0}^{\infty} b_k</m> converges, then so does <m>\sum_\limits{k=0}^{\infty} a_k</m> 
         </p>
    </statement>
</task>
<task>
    <statement>
        <p>
            Prove that if <m>\sum_\limits{k=0}^{\infty} |a_k|</m> converges, then so does <m>\sum_\limits{k=0}^{\infty} a_k</m> (absolute convergence implies convergence). <em>Hint:</em> Use absolute convergence to show that the sequence of partial sums of <m>\sum_\limits{k=0}^{\infty} a_k</m> is a Cauchy sequence.
        </p>
    </statement>
</task>

    
</exercise>


<exercise><title>Uniform vs. Pointwise Convergence of Series</title>
<introduction>
    <p>
        Here we review what it means for series of functions to converge pointwise and uniformly and do an example.
    </p>
</introduction>
<task>
    <statement>
        <p>
            Let <m>\{f_k(x)\}_{k=0}^{\infty}</m> be a sequence of real-valued functions of a real variable. Define what it means for the series
            <md>
                \sum_{k=0}^{\infty}f_k(x)
            </md>
            to converge to a function <m>f</m> pointwise and uniformly (two definitions).
        </p>
    </statement>
</task>
<task>
    <statement>
        <p>
            Prove that the Taylor/Maclaurin series for <m>\sin(x)</m> and <m>\cos(x)</m> do not converge uniformly to these functions on <m>\mathbb{R}</m>.
        </p>
    </statement>
</task>
</exercise>

<exercise><title>The Weierstrass <m>M</m>-Test</title>
<statement>
    <p>
        An important result for proving Fourier series converge is the following. Prove it.
    </p>
    <p>
        Suppose <m>\{f_k(x)\}_{k=0}^{\infty}</m> is a sequence of functions such that <m>|f_k(x)|\leq M_k</m> (for all <m>x\in\mathbb{R}</m>) for some sequence of positive constants <m>M_k</m>, where <m>\sum\limits_{k=0}^{\infty} M_k</m> converges. Then the series 
            <md>
                \sum_{k=0}^{\infty}f_k(x)
            </md>
        converges absolutely and uniformly on <m>\mathbb{R}</m>.
    </p>
</statement>

    
</exercise>
    


</page>


</worksheet>
